		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../atem.png" alt="ATEM 2006 SI"></a><br><code>atem2006s/paper07</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">ATEM 2006 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Evaluating Formal Properties of Feature Diagram Languages</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/PatrickHeymans.html">Patrick Heymans</a>, <a href="../profile/PierreYvesSchobbens.html">Pierre-Yves Schobbens</a>, <a href="../profile/JeanChristopheTrigaux.html">Jean-Christophe Trigaux</a>, <a href="../profile/YvesBontemps.html">Yves Bontemps</a>, <a href="../profile/RaimundasMatulevičius.html">Raimundas Matulevičius</a>, <a href="../profile/AndreasClaßen.html">Andreas Claßen</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1049/iet-sen:20070055">10.1049/iet-sen:20070055</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagM">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> Feature diagrams are treated as variability modelling languages for software product lines, and the paper’s main focus is comparing their variability semantics.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> It grounds comparison in formal syntax/semantics (comparative semantics) and uses formal criteria to assess language properties.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> A substantial part is about (re-)engineering modelling languages by clarifying constructs/semantics and identifying ambiguities and expressiveness trade-offs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The method analyses and compares language definitions (FD notations) to discriminate between competing language designs.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
